@flexiarg plos-npt-with-small-n/theory-as-heuristic-not-law
@title Frame the Theory as a Heuristic Device, and Name Its Limits
@keywords theory, NPT, heuristic, over-claiming, framework-critique, hedge, remedy-in-design
@audience paper authors, qualitative researchers, PLOS ONE drafters
@tone technical
@style pattern
@source-dois [10.1371/journal.pone.0195890 10.1371/journal.pone.0282612]
@references [plos-npt-with-small-n/framework-spine-with-empirical-ribs plos-npt-with-small-n/coherence-first-when-using-npt]

! conclusion: Present the analytic framework as a heuristic device that organised and aided the analysis, not as a causal or explanatory law the data prove.  Where the framework has a known limitation, name it and show how the study's design compensates.  This pre-empts the reviewer charge that the theory is being over-claimed, while still crediting it with analytic value.

  + context: The ERAS exemplar repeatedly downgrades NPT to "a potentially useful heuristic device" and, having isolated one construct, turns the difficulty of separating it from the others into an explicit finding about the constructs' interconnectedness.  The stroke-rehab exemplar names a standard criticism of NPT — its bias toward professional action — and states that including patient interviews addresses it.  Both grant the framework usefulness while disclaiming over-reach.

  + IF:
    The pattern operates on the axis: theory-as-proven-law <-> theory-as-acknowledged-heuristic.
    Irreducible: a qualitative study cannot prove a theory; claiming it does invites rejection, while denying the theory any role wastes the analytic structure.  The heuristic framing occupies the defensible middle: useful lens, not demonstrated mechanism.

  + HOWEVER:
    Real costs: calling the framework "just" a heuristic can read as underselling the theoretical contribution.  The discipline is to credit specific analytic work the framework did (organising findings, surfacing the interconnection of constructs) while declining the causal claim — usefulness without over-reach.
    Active dynamic: authors invested in a framework drift toward treating its constructs as real entities the data confirm.  The stronger move is to treat the constructs as lenses and to name where the lens distorts.

    + FAILURE-MODES:
      - Theory-reified: constructs are written as causal forces the data "prove," over-claiming explanatory power.
      - Limitation-unnamed: a well-known weakness of the framework goes unmentioned, so a reviewer raises it instead.
      - Heuristic-without-credit: the framework is dismissed as merely a heuristic with no account of what it actually contributed.

  + THEN: Credit the framework as a lens and bound its claims.
    + COMPOSITIONS:
      (1) Heuristic-framing statement.
          Schema: {:framework <name> :role "heuristic device" :contributed <organising/surfacing work> :not-claimed "causal mechanism"}
          Effect: secures analytic value without over-reach.
      (2) Limitation-then-remedy.
          Schema: {:known-criticism <of the framework> :remedy-in-design <what the study did about it>}
          Effect: converts a framework critique into a design strength.
      (3) Interconnection-as-finding.
          Schema: {:isolated-construct <X> :difficulty "cannot cleanly separate from others" :as-finding true}
          Effect: turns the awkwardness of using one construct into a substantive observation.

    + CHECK:
      Engaged when the framework is credited with specific analytic work but not claimed to be proven, and its known limits are named and addressed.  Failing when constructs are reified as proven mechanisms, or the framework's weaknesses go unmentioned.
